
export const ox = {
    introduction: `Hail, Diligent Ox, a veritable Gibraltar. You are an indomitable fortress. This zodiac sign might have been named Bulldozer instead of Ox. You are an inherently temperate individual who deeply values rigor, hard work, strength of character, and, most importantly, tangible outcomes! You are capable of persisting at a task for longer and applying yourself more intensely than anyone else. You spare no effort. You detest being defeated, so you simply never surrender. Some may describe you as slow; others might complain that you are clumsy. In reality, you proceed at your own comfortable pace and refuse to be rushed or pressured by impulsive, fleeting individuals. You believe in simplicity and accomplishment. Lightheartedness in business matters exasperates you.
You are capable of profound, enduring love, yet romantic gestures leave you unaffected. You prefer practical action over sentimental displays like beds of roses and vials of exotic perfumes. You approach life with great seriousness, but life does not always reciprocate that favor. You typically do not speak much, but you possess a remarkable talent for storytelling. If you are truly aiming for results, utilize that distinctive flair. Engage in conversation with the conservative Rooster you have been wanting to invite to dinner. Share some pink sparkling wine with a talkative Rat, or send dozens of white roses to a luxury-loving Snake. They are all well-equipped to respond positively to your unique method of persuasion. The initial two phases of your life will be characterized by strenuous effort. During the second adult stage, a misunderstanding between you and a neighbor or colleague may lead to a profound, long-lasting disagreement. Do not lose hope. Your old age will be both lengthy and healthy, with peace of mind becoming your top priority after the age of fifty.
My advice? Yes. Lighten up. And cease judging others by your own elevated standards. You will only experience disappointment. Nobody (except you, my dear Ox) is flawless.`,
    elements: {
        Wood: `The Wood Ox is the most exceptionally hardworking among all Oxen. If you find that the Wood Ox is not engaged in working, studying, composing, or striving to lift a massive weight, you might reasonably assume he is no longer alive. However, even in death, the Wood Ox is not the kind of individual to quietly fade away, leaving behind pleasant memories of a romantic, lyrical spirit. When this person departs, all the water seems to drain from the swimming pool, leaving a colossal, resounding impression of their significant, creative, and impactful presence.
The Wood Ox is not universally regarded as a pleasant individual. On the contrary! He is what my mother used to describe as "a real piece of work," a relentless combatant against all forces he does not already command. In an effort to dominate, direct, achieve superiority, and emerge as the controlling factor in every undertaking, this fearless, cunning, brilliant, and persistent person allows no obstacle to deter him. His guiding principle is "Progress Gratia Progress"—advancement for its own sake—and if it means stepping over a few fallen individuals along the way, well, the Wood Ox simply says, "that's life."
I once knew a Wood Ox whose father traditionally made bricks in the French countryside but earned very little money. At eighteen, when my friend completed her schooling, she began working for her father in the office. She was convinced that her father was mismanaging everything, so she informed him of this. They argued. This Ox packed her belongings and left home. Four years later, her father fell ill. The brick business was in its usual precarious state. The Ox was called home to assist. While her father was unwell, the Ox went to the factory. She contacted a bank or two, secured capital, purchased cement-block manufacturing equipment, installed it, reassigned the old brick salesmen to sell the blocks to builders, and began accumulating a fortune in profits. When a few former customers inquired about old-style bricks, the Ox informed them that her father's company no longer produced bricks and that all the best builders had transitioned to cement blocks. When her father, who was not yet sixty-five, recovered, he returned to work. But the Ox had moved into his office, relocating him to a freshly painted anteroom. "Papa," the Ox informed him, "you can relax. Sit back. You only need to assist me now." She had effectively retired her father from his own business! And she boasts about it. It is the first in the Ox's collection of "See How Wonderful I Am" narratives.
The Ox's father passed away—I suspect from a broken heart, but the Ox does not interpret it that way. "My father lacked resilience. He used to take time off to work in his garden. Sometimes, he would even go fishing. I had to rescue his business. Just to demonstrate how truly weak he was after I semi-retired him, he fell into a deep depression. He died before the next Christmas." I find this story shocking. But for the Wood-born Ox, whose constitution is as robust as its resolve, it is either its way or no way. There are no clever solutions other than its own. No one else works as diligently as it does, so no one deserves as much. It takes everything, claims it as its own, and then lends it back to its rightful owners.
Wood Oxen are formidable individuals. However, despite their expertise in the art of dominance, they can be remarkably generous. The Wood Ox cherishes nature, children, and family, and reveres those who know how to cultivate nature in return for its abundant gifts. Whether they are farmers, doctors, artists, or householders, Wood Oxen will always assist those they believe are doing a 'good job,' exerting all their strength and achieving success.
One intriguing benefit of befriending Wood Oxen is that they are often incredibly witty, perceiving life satirically and communicating their ironic perspective. Although they may engage in much romantic small talk in bed and are utterly inept at candle-lit dinners, Wood Oxen possess sublime eloquence. When they utilize this gift to enhance their presence or to expand their business, no one communicates more effectively. Wood Oxen always know how to select the perfect phrase to convey the pain, the humor, or the sensation they experienced. If you are fortunate enough to persuade one of these taciturn individuals to tell you a story, you are in for a delightful experience.
Wood Oxen are frequently unaware that many people dislike them. They disregard the feelings of those they do not favor. You will never hear one of these resolute individuals express regret about divorcing their spouse, quitting their boss, or moving far away from their aging mother. Wood Oxen simply believe they should proceed. If they do not cultivate many heartfelt friendships and must endure numerous adversaries, it does not concern them. If friendship requires them to concede even an inch of progress, they will abandon the friend for the sake of advancement.
Although teamwork is hardly its forte, the Wood Ox enjoys being married and raising a family. However, at best, being the wife or husband, child, or even sibling of this character is challenging. A Wood Ox can only be managed by someone weaker than itself. Do not challenge what it says with a retort or a taunt. Never disagree with it. Do not respond when it orders you to bring coffee, make love, or walk the dog. Only your passive inertia can provoke even a slight reaction in this excessively self-important person's impenetrable ego. It possesses so much willpower that it is baffled by a lack of resolve in others. To irritate this individual, act as though you agree with everything it does and says. Play obedient-pet games, complete with whimpering if necessary—but continue doing exactly as you please. Provided that, in this outwardly subservient manner, you keep your intentions hidden, the Wood Ox is guaranteed to become your devoted servant.`,
        Fire: `The most agreeable way to begin a description of the intricate Fire Ox is to caution you that Fire influences the Ox in precisely the same manner it affects dynamite, jet planes, and helium-filled airships. Where there is already an abundance of latent power, the Fire element leads to excess and, at times, even to catastrophe. Unlike other Oxen, the Fire Ox is impatient. Like them, it desires to advance and reach destinations, but it struggles more with adopting a long-term perspective. Oxen do not often risk making fools of themselves. Most are natural planners. They prefer to observe developments from a safe distance before entering the fray. However, the Fire Ox's long-term view is inverted; it acts impulsively before considering the consequences.
Like most Oxen, this one assumes it is inherently superior. Do not give it a second thought. The Fire Ox is inherently better and more deserving of success, money, and whatever else it perceives, desires, and acquires. To the appealing Oxen's blend of self-assurance and strength of will, this creature adds an endearing new characteristic: moral self-righteousness. Fire Oxen fear nothing—not even ridicule—and will forge ahead, brandishing slogans as if bound to their moral exhortations, proselytizing speeches, and "enlightened" schemes until death separates them. This can be terribly tedious. It can even be self-destructive. But Fire Oxen will persist, waving their fiery ideals, displaying their moral indignation openly, and often losing the respect they are due from their peers. The inverse of this apparent disadvantage is that the Fire Ox is often a genius, remarkably successful, and frequently accurate in selecting its objectives. Warren Beatty, Robert Redford, Jack Nicholson, Bill Cosby, and Dustin Hoffman have all been exceedingly outspoken in public, pushed the limits of their talents in many unconventional areas of show business, and have all emerged with an excellent reputation.
The Ox's inherent strength, when combined with Fire's dynamism and vigor, can indeed create an exceptionally effective human being. Furthermore, work is never an issue; this person possesses extraordinary powers of endurance. Because it is fortunate enough to believe so fervently that it is always correct, it can appear inconsiderate and overbearing. Its justification? It is idealistic and a true champion for its cause. Any self-respecting Fire Ox will defend its beliefs against all odds. This irritating trait often leads the Fire Ox to triumph.
It is frequently bolder than it is intelligent, more willful than it is attuned to what is truly happening. For this Ox, the battle is the most satisfying part of the conflict. It also desires some applause, but it is not truly seeking one grand achievement or a lifelong victory that would allow it to settle down and raise a family. The Fire Ox is often engaged in conflict and is more than willing to defend its ideals indefinitely.
Sadly, this stubborn individual is more often respected than loved. It lacks subtlety and does not always know the best way to relate to others. It is also ruthless. It may glorify everything associated with tradition until it no longer serves its purpose. Then it may well glorify something new and label it traditional.
I suppose the best way to interact with this unyielding, appealingly active person is to begin by being strong-minded—at least a Tiger, or a Dragon, a philosophical Snake, or an utterly indifferent Rooster. To impress it, demonstrate your strength upfront. Occasionally, startle your Fire Ox by showing it a different perspective. This will not cure its shortsightedness, but it might sufficiently jolt its ego to give it a hint about how far off the mark it truly is. Otherwise, to capture its attention, try tickling the soles of its feet. It is certain to pretend to dislike that. But ultimately, only pure silliness and sweet, innocent (yet powerful) love can subdue the explosive Fire Oxen and encourage it to stop taking itself so excessively seriously.
The Fire Ox can be a family-oriented person. If it chooses to have children, it is deeply responsible and committed to the well-being of its spouse and offspring. It will also govern their domain and refuses to tolerate any back talk or criticism. It can be kind and makes a generous parent. It may not be very receptive to children who complain or share their troubles—emotions are not its strong suit. But if anyone were to attack a member of its family—even its good-for-nothing brother-in-law who cannot find a decent job and drinks too much—the Fire Ox will rise up and protect its own.`,
        Earth: `The Earth Ox is the intrusive Ox. It is excessively curious, meddlesome, and interfering. It believes it knows best, and often it does. Generally, Oxen consider themselves somewhat superior to other people. Earth Oxen not only think they are better; they are convinced they were born to guide others, to instruct those less fortunate on how to live, and to command them. What we have here is a highly nature-oriented, grounded, power-obsessed megalomaniac whose ability to detect flaws in life's various situations is practically unerring.
You will rarely encounter a more self-assured person. This Ox is not only self-reliant—it is convinced that you are not. Ask the Earth Ox a foolish question, and you will receive a profound sigh of impatience in return. "How can you be so obtuse?" it might groan. "I already informed you that the mouse controls the arrow on the screen. Are you too unintelligent to learn how to operate a computer?" Do not let this condescending attitude deter you. Ox groans signify very little. All that tut-tutting and complaining is merely a defensive mechanism, a method of humiliation designed to keep you off balance so that you do not notice it has gained too much weight or dyed its hair green. I am not attempting to excuse this Ox's tyrannical teaching methods, but its behavior is often so offensively pushy that it requires considerable patience and much tolerance.
Earth Oxen firmly believe that the true objective in life is to achieve perfection in every area. They do not flinch at the prospect of intense hard work. They are perpetually organized and cannot tolerate excessive spontaneity. The Earth Ox is not the life and soul of the party. It leads. It is never truly an integral part of the group.
But it is brave. And it is bold. Audacity is its defining characteristic. Consider it—Earth and Ox combined equal a bulldozer. This individual will relentlessly advance, like a caterpillar-tractor, over any number of obstacles to enter any board meeting, cabinet meeting, or bedroom it feels it should be permitted to enter without knocking. As long as it needs something and desires it, it considers it its own.
Now, such a seize-and-take approach may seem horrifyingly ruthless to you, but the Earth Ox behaves as it does because (believe it or not) it is insecure! Yes. Insecurity is the root cause of all bullying on earth, and Earth Ox bullies are no exception. This person secretly suffers from a fear of being unloved, rejected, and abandoned. It is never certain of its best friend or even its best romantic partner. It is well aware that it is clumsy and lacks skill in appreciating subtleties. So... to protect its own tender feelings, it employs aggressive tactics to preempt any potential aggression from others.
We must forgive it. It genuinely does not know any better. Even the most successful Earth Ox is somewhat awkward, an unsophisticated individual in refined attire, who wishes it had never become so prominent as to be compelled to socialize with all these splendid people who only make it feel more like a country bumpkin. What the Earth Ox intended to do when it decided to take over the world was to lead the populace. But it did not anticipate that they would ask it to learn to drink champagne, engage in small talk, or dance the Tango.
Consider this. If you awakened one day and faced the responsibility of guiding the world, it might be less than easy to maintain your composure. Since the Earth Ox was born with this certainty of leadership and is fundamentally a sincere person, when it undertakes the immense task of shepherding the world, it desires everything to proceed smoothly. After all, the outcome of all human endeavor rests with it. If things go well, it feels it is performing its job correctly, and then it can afford to be in a good mood. If the operations become stalled (which they invariably do), this poor, overly responsible creature believes it is entirely its fault.
Does it become depressed and sulk? Will it explode and overturn tables and chairs? Or might it resort to alcohol or drugs? No. The domineering Earth Ox who observes that its subjects have flagrantly disregarded its rules abandons the leader role and opts for dictator. It is convinced that because it defines the boundaries, it need not hesitate to overstep them—constantly.
One way to help this excessively bold person feel more comfortable in their own skin would be to show them how to curb their ego-driven exploits. But to do this, you would have to persuade them to accept advice, and they despise advice. They know everything, so why waste time heeding other people's chatter? The one sure path to its heart is through its stomach. This person enjoys eating. Drown it in rich, country-style soups. Lure her away from her chores with a plateful of lobster delicacies. Then play a thirty-minute CD recording of applause—the Earth Ox's preferred lullaby.
To the Earth Ox, sex is a physical act. Romance may be charming, but it is not their method of communication. The Earth Ox engages in sex; it does not "make love." Do not expect an Earth Ox lover to confess intricate fantasies or devise elaborate scenarios to awaken your diminished desire in the bedroom. When you go on picnics with Earth Oxen, leave your poetry books at home. A good hearty meal, a glass of wine, and a little physical intimacy will suffice for them.
Finally, although the Earth Ox is a meticulous rule-maker and a disciplined self-starter, it is often literary or artistic in some specialized field. It always finishes what it begins and can be relied upon for promptness and trusted for its fundamental honesty. However, its blindness to its own fallibility may lead it to commit some dreadful errors, and as profound guilt and denial follow, it may lose confidence and become impossibly defensive. If by the age of forty, it does not become more flexible, the Earth Ox can expect to live out a bitter old age, rigid and unyielding, forever lacking a sense of humor about its own flaws.`,
        Metal: `The Metal Ox is the most socially skilled Ox. It possesses charisma; there is a magical quality about Metal Oxen. An aura or halo surrounds their spirit, and it radiates. People are automatically drawn to the Metal Ox's warm public demeanor. The charm that emanates from it is natural, unpretentious—and captivating. In true Ox fashion, it harbors great personal ambition, desires to achieve success in its chosen fields, and sees no reason why it should not become the best in its profession. Consider a few of the 1901 Ox individuals, for example: Walt Disney was talented, but there were many animators in Hollywood at that time. If he had not possessed the crisp, resolute drive and determination of a Metal Ox, he probably would not have created the colossal industry that bears his name today. Or Andre Malraux—a giant of intellect. Had he been born a Dog or a Pig, he might have been content to write poetry and teach at university. Instead, he became a global traveler, art critic, cultural minister of France, public figure, and a creator of strict laws regarding the preservation of France's artistic heritage. Or take Eddie Murphy, born in 1961: He was already working on TV as a teenager, writing his own hilarious scripts and performing them in nightclubs. By the age of twenty-two, he was a star. Now he is a wealthy and famous man who can select which roles he desires in movies.
This person is not your typical stay-at-home, pipe-and-slippers, beer-and-peanuts individual. Metal Oxen do not usually languish, waiting for Godot or the Tooth Fairy to assure them they are loved. If you are the partner of a Metal Ox, remember that you are expected to be not only faithful, loyal, and true, but also dutiful, cheerful, and energetic. We already know that the Metal Ox strives hard to reach the pinnacle, but because not every day brings sufficient triumph, it will become frustrated and often return home in a foul mood. During these times, it is unreachable, lost in a haze of gloom, sulking.
As far as the Metal Ox is concerned, it is your duty (or at least its family's responsibility) either to help it emerge from this state or to remove yourself from the situation. You can argue, and it will argue back. You can shout, and it will do likewise. You can even reason, and it will engage you in a debate. But your Metal Ox will not accept criticism gracefully. It cannot tolerate reassessment of its methods or approach by anyone other than itself. It refuses to consider another's point of view. Even if it admires it, it cannot accept being wrong. Its pride obstructs its rational thought.
The Metal Ox's refusal of external interference reveals another unfortunate aspect of this charming person's stubborn character. Metal Oxen tend to distrust the judgment of those closest to them in favor of that of a complete stranger—a hazardous attitude, as strangers may attempt to deceive it.
This Ox is also stubbornly patriotic. It firmly believes that might makes right and becomes more conservative with age. It is neurotically nostalgic: in the past, it believes, the world functioned smoothly. It yearns for things to be right again, for people to be straightforward, for rain to fall only at night. A Disneyland-like world of obedient children and pleasant music, without the presence of villains, is the Metal Ox's ideal dream-world.
Since life does not often unfold in that manner, the Metal Ox is frequently in a state of semi-despair, complaining and grumbling, and assuming that everything, from today's lazy youth to hippies or hooligans or the breakdown of dress codes in banking institutions, is to blame. It finds fault with everyone except its own family. Never criticize its work, its person, or its family. Only it is permitted to dissect them—at home, behind closed doors. For public display, Mr. and Mrs. Metal Ox and all the little Metal Oxen must appear to be exemplary citizens.
The artistic side of the Metal Ox is its greatest redeeming quality. Its true contributions come through its creative endeavors, which are always imaginative and well-intentioned. If the Metal Ox's at-home personality were as sweet and fun-loving as its skillful, lyrical creations, it would not be perceived as such a gloomy individual by its family and close friends.
The Metal Ox is an exceptionally serious individual whose amiable public persona belies the stern, grumpy one who blusters on the front porch. It is as challenging to live with as it is critical of almost everything and everyone it is close to. Its sense of humor may be sharp on life's grand stage, but its ability to laugh at itself is nonexistent. It is intuitive and will listen to your problems and offer advice, but if you do not follow its suggestions, it will take offense. The Metal Ox is dependable and extraordinarily hardworking. It is an excellent provider and will always ensure its loved ones have a roof over their heads. If you possess abundant, easy-going patience, consider a relationship with a Metal Ox. If you struggle to accept criticism, steer clear of it and find yourself a gentler companion.`,
        Water: `Water (believe it or not) imbues the Ox with an additional measure of profoundness. This individual is a thoughtful, planning, plotting, and steady worker who consistently adopts a long-term perspective. A robust rice-paddy water buffalo, symbolizing fertility and patience, service and strength, offers a true depiction of this kind, yet stern and unwavering soul.
If it can help it, no Water Ox ever resorts to begging for a living. It is clever and hardworking, and will eventually dominate and thrive in every professional undertaking. It is strong and persistent, accomplishing tasks in a deliberate manner that suits its measured temperament. Water Oxen make little noise and demand little attention. They always advance, slowly. They begin a task and labor at it with regularity and certainty. They do not require modern methods or technological marvels to achieve success. Water Oxen are born knowing how to triumph.
No one should obstruct a Water Ox. Because they are patient, they are slow to react. Instead of confronting their adversaries directly, they simmer for a long while, quietly going about their business, saying nothing, and waiting to observe how situations unfold. Then, just as they are about to reach their boiling point, they accelerate and strike! They put an end to their rage by annihilating the enemy.
Water Oxen are not content with short-term solutions. For them, if something is worth doing, it merits being thoroughly considered, reflected upon, and deliberated until all aspects have been examined under a microscope—no hasty risk-taking here. They have all the time in the world to ponder while awaiting some impulsive individual to make a tactical error.
The Water Ox is most content in the countryside. Deep down, it is a farmer (usually a prosperous one), and it is also a leader. It will champion the causes of less fortunate farmers or conduct the Rotary Club orchestra. The Water Ox is not lazy, but as its pace is unhurried, it can be perceived as lethargic. From an outsider's perspective, the Water Ox never appears very busy. It does not rush about trying to accomplish sixty things at once, nor does it passively allow life to control it. It learned this at birth: steady perseverance wins the race.
Outwardly, the Water Ox is never frantic or pressured, yet it often achieves significantly more than those who rush ahead and overlook hundreds of daily activities. The Water Ox enjoys routine, reveres punctuality, and takes pleasure in doing things as they "should" be done. It desires to wake up and retire to bed at the same hour every day. It feels secure knowing that lunch is at noon and dinner at eight.
The Water Ox is profoundly family-oriented. It cannot live without its relatives surrounding it. It is possessive and jealous of their affections and always wishes them to conform as it does. The Water Ox is the type of parent who has five children and assigns each a profession at birth: Charlie will be a lawyer, Arielle a doctor, and so on. No arguments, no substitutions.
The unwavering resolve of the Water Ox should be bottled and marketed to indecisive individuals. Add to that a clear understanding of reality. It comprehends the pitfalls of human interaction so well that, if it desired, it could be president of the universe. But this rustic individual wants no part in politics. It feels awkward at sophisticated parties and is inhibited in small talk. It is happiest when comfortably settled in its solid stone house, in its cozy living room, surrounded by old friends and family. Traditional feasts elevate its appreciation for ritual. It loves to cook and eat the food it grows, preserves, and prepares with loving care. It is a country person with the financial success of a bank president.
The Water Ox is a loving, sensitive soul and will gladly listen to and empathize with other people's troubles. It will take time to contemplate a complex situation and will provide a thoughtful response. Neither egotistical nor self-centered, it does, however, prefer things to be managed its way. It is generous to those it loves, always giving them the benefit of the doubt and a helping hand when they are in difficulty.
It is, however, rare for a Water Ox to retract an opinion. It is stubborn and uncompromising, firmly believing that it possesses the sole truth. It never openly questions its own methods or asks, "Am I doing the right thing?" But it is secretly sentimental and can be swayed through its emotions. The Water Ox finds affection irresistible. Finally, Water bestows a substantial dose of vengefulness upon this unsophisticated individual. Anyone who betrays or wrongs a Water Ox will regret the day they did. The Water Ox could teach an elephant lessons in remembering every detail of pain ever inflicted upon it. Water Oxen wait, think, ruminate, conspire, plot, and can even kill. Stay clear of their resentment.`,
    },
    compatibilities: {
    "Rat": "Union between these two signs guarantees matrimonial stability. The Ox provides the energetic Rat with the grounding it lacks, and the Rat subtly influences the Ox's conventionality and resistance to change, enlivening what could otherwise be a dull, plodding existence. This combination fits well, with each partner complementing the other's sharper characteristics. The Ox's steadfastness offers the Rat the kind of security it requires. The devoted Ox will willingly assume the role of provider, which allows the Rat to act as the family protector. The sociable Rat enjoys hosting parties and attending social functions. This arrangement is ideal for the quiet Ox, who, without the Rat's exuberant nature, would simply remain at home contemplating. Each partner is content to fulfill their respective role. Alluring and meticulous, a Rat serves as a perfect assistant for an Ox in business, going to great lengths to encourage the Ox’s career. Of course, the Ox demands complete fidelity. Despite an occasional nagging desire to stray, the Rat will largely remain faithful. What about passion? Neither the Rat nor the Ox is excessively concerned with the whimsical idea of extravagant lovemaking practices. Their sex life will be lusty, though routine.",
    "Ox": "The combined strength of a double-Ox marriage could cultivate forty acres before breakfast. Being dutiful and methodical, they mutually protect and provide for each other. Their household will be blessed with a rare harmony, so perfectly balanced that any external influence might disrupt its equilibrium. Anticipate a certain healthy predictability. In their organized kitchen, this couple meticulously plans to uphold their shared need for order. Despite their fundamental agreement, this strong-willed pair sometimes struggles with sharing authority. Oxen prefer to dominate, and each expects the other to obey. Depending on their Western signs, planetary influences, and other factors, they can likely resolve their differences amicably. Ox couples are mutually stubborn and will not be inclined to disclose minor disagreements—not even to each other. Rather than expressing dissatisfaction, Oxen will deny their differences, maintain an appearance of marital bliss, and suffer silently, diligently persevering, accepting the heavy burdens they perceive they must bear. Stasis becomes them. Their wholesome lovemaking brings consistent sexual fulfillment to this marriage. Passionate exuberance and emotional outbursts are unfamiliar to the Ox. Their sex life will be healthy, but it probably will not awaken the children. With both partners diligently working, an Ox-filled home will not lack financial security. Ample money will be earned but rarely spent foolishly. The Ox permits no frivolous expenditures.",
    "Tiger": "This pairing is disastrous. No matter how you analyze it, this combination is destined for a tumultuous journey. Both possess an unyielding will, supported by the capacity to exert it. Equally self-possessed and determined, the stubborn Ox and the temperamental Tiger are better known as adversaries than as collaborators. Frankly, this quarrelsome duo is best suited for entanglement within a boxing ring. Often, the Tiger disrupts the Ox's tranquil day by instigating trouble. The stoical Ox desires only to remain close to home and continue its steady work. It must exercise considerable patience with the boisterous Tiger, and the Ox finds that exhausting. The rebellious Tiger roars off to a trade union demonstration, complaining bitterly about the mundane, dreary Ox, while the Ox intimidates the Tiger, accusing it of everything from incurable restlessness to outright insanity. If a third round of conflict occurs in the bedroom, there is hope for reconciliation. The Tiger's raw sensuality melts the Ox's icy resistance. With the Tiger, the inhibited Ox feels liberated. Twenty-four-hour truces may result. Even so, this union is best suited for friendship or a business partnership, where dual strong wills can achieve genuine progress. The Tiger/Ox emotional match is a constant struggle. It is not romantically promising.",
    "Rabbit": "This is a cozy pairing. Nestled against a rock-solid Ox, the Cat will have plenty to purr about. The Ox provides the anxious Cat with security, allowing the Cat to dedicate time to creative activities without having to worry about finances. In return, the Cat, naturally endowed with refinement, provides its more unrefined counterpart with much-needed sophistication. The Ox's bossiness is easily managed by a Cat, who typically chooses to avoid conflict. Quiet and submissive, the Cat is content to take a secondary role and allow the Bull to assert dominance, feeling secure in the presence of a strong, forceful mate. To show gratitude, the Cat showers the Ox with affection. Of course, the self-sacrificing Ox finds excessive displays of affection difficult to tolerate and may avoid gestures of tenderness or mock them. This attitude could prove frustrating for the affectionate Cat, who adores cuddling. With luck, in time, its feline companion will melt the Ox's icy resistance and perhaps even teach it a romantic trick or two.",
    "Dragon": "Be prepared for frequent late-night disagreements in an Ox/Dragon combination. Both individuals believe they are more correct than anyone else. The Dragon attempts to impose its will over the opinionated Ox, and the Bull retaliates with its own assertiveness. The Ox has little patience for vanity. The Ox's indifference to the Dragon's fiery appearance is a constant source of disappointment for the Dragon's ego. The glamorous, extravagant Dragon loves to spend money, but with the Ox meticulously counting pennies, it feels constrained and uneasy. The Dragon's tendency to flirt unsettles the faithful Ox, who rarely strays from a good sexual union—it simply does not have the time, being too busy working. With so much conflict, how can this duo reconcile? Their mutual love of home and family could rescue them from complete despair. Both enjoy sexual intimacy, although the Ox's routine techniques may bore the Dragon, whose sentimental nature yearns for fluffy clouds of pink cotton candy to enhance lovemaking. It will not often experience fireworks with the Ox. Furthermore, the methodical Ox expects a regular daily schedule. The Dragon, however, prefers a more unpredictable timetable, such as intense, stormy sexual encounters for a week followed by three weeks of peace and quiet. While an excellent business partnership, this union is not recommended for either marriage or romance—unless the Dragon is free to roam and seek excitement elsewhere.",
    "Snake": "A nimble Snake entwines itself around an Ox's yoke and accompanies it on its journey. The Ox welcomes its agile passenger and steadily progresses through life with contentment. A Snake feels comfortable in the Ox's presence. Yet, the fickle Snake possesses an appetite for new experiences—especially those yet unexplored. Oxen are devoutly monogamous. Deep down, of course, the Snake is devoted to the Ox, whose stability is crucially important for the Snake's survival. If the Ox can learn to curb its suspicious nature and control a jealous temper, this creature can retain an appealing Snake partner better than anyone else. After all, the Ox possesses all the money, power, and patience, and Snakes adore all those qualities. Should the Ox begin to worry over failed ventures or depleted reserves, the Snake must subtly lead it to bed. The Ox is happy to comply with lusty quantity, but to prevent the reptile's attention from wandering, it must develop more imaginative foreplay. This union can be a good one if the Ox can remain courageous and undaunted by a challenging (yet fascinating) Snake mate.",
    "Horse": "This pairing is exhausting! These two get along so poorly that the effort expended in trying is hardly worth the outcome. What a struggle! The conventional Ox desires to tame the wild, independent Horse, whose sole impulse is to gallop far away from an authoritarian Ox partner. Horses prefer to make their own decisions and detest meddlesome suggestions. The stubborn Ox incessantly dictates and advises. If the Ox interferes too strongly with the Horse's single-mindedness, the arrogant Horse will seize every opportunity to humiliate the unsuspecting Ox—in public! The best aspect of this marriage is the work ethic; it is exceptionally high. Both partners will labor and carry burdens without complaint. That is the positive side. But the Horse simply will not conform to the Ox's ways. It drives the Ox to distraction with wildly imaginative ideas, such as painting the house pink, getting married in black pajamas, or taking home a STOP sign from in front of the police station. The Ox fumes and sulks. The Horse merely laughs, convinced it is married to a dullard. Sexually, this strong-willed combination will already be dissatisfied on their honeymoon. The Horse, like a wild bronco unleashed in a corral, utterly overwhelms the Ox's reserve. The slow-paced Ox is still in a state of undress when the Horse is already intensely engaged. No harmony will characterize this union.",
    "Goat": "In the beginning, the delicate Goat appears to be a great catch for a domineering Ox. But one must never judge a Goat by appearances! Although gentle, Goats are not easily controlled. I caution all Oxen against this union. Initially, you will feel a surge of power alongside this dainty mountain creature. But after several shared excursions, your inflated ego will deflate like a tired soufflé. The Goat complains incessantly, and you (slowly but surely) lose interest. The patient Ox tolerates the Goat's lackadaisical attitude for a while, but soon comes to believe that the Goat is not only lazy but also without direction. A hardworking Ox simply cannot comprehend the Goat's inertia. Content to be dependent on others, the Goat simply does not feel the need to work itself to exhaustion. Does not the dedicated Bull provide more than enough for the household? After a while, as the Ox is so docile and responsible, the Goat finds it simply tedious. The Goat enjoys sleeping on different sides of the bed every night for amusement, which exasperates the rigid Ox, who cannot bear the thought of breaking routine. Even in bed, the unadventurous Ox struggles to keep up with all the different Goat positions. This is an awkward couple. Each would be better off without the other.",
    "Monkey": "If the Ox can abandon stubborn conformity and trust its beloved Monkey, the Monkey can significantly enhance the quality of the Ox's life. In return for the Monkey's gift of freedom, the Ox will provide security to its Monkey mate. Much to everyone’s surprise, the Ox, typically angered by any disruption of routine, is captivated by the clever Monkey. The Monkey, in turn, strives harder to entertain and enchant its faithful mate. Both are fundamentally practical and goal-oriented. Moreover, Monkeys can teach Oxen to look beyond themselves, to be genuinely kind to others, and to assist the less fortunate. Charity brings a special thrill to the Ox. It is grateful to the Monkey for opening its eyes to the needs of the impoverished. In the bedroom, expect the imaginative Monkey to invigorate the Ox's predictable technique. With the Monkey's agile guidance, the Ox can anticipate learning far more than a few new moves. It may even learn how to soar!",
    "Rooster": "Should you be fortunate enough to have found each other, remain together. People consistently notice an Ox/Rooster couple. 'Look how content they are!' they remark. Astrologers in China recommend this as one of the most favorable unions ever! Together, your lives will be enriched by a blend of effortless sociability and unwavering security. Individually, the Ox and the Rooster can be equally meticulous, anxious, and perfectionistic. One might expect this pairing to come together and then self-destruct. But, for some reason, they discover peace. This traditional couple lives strictly by the rules. The Ox performs everything correctly, and the Rooster follows suit. They purchase their first home at the appropriate stage of life, have children when expected, and retire to their beautiful country residence when they become wealthy—which often happens very quickly. Both are keen, capable workers. They are not particularly fond of social outings, preferring to remain close to home. Children will be more than welcome here. This stable pair provides great security for a family. Not known for passion or recklessness, their sexual intimacy reflects their practical lifestyle. No embellishments, just basic, normal lovemaking. Two naturally harmonious signs should ensure this happy marriage is long-lived and successful.",
    "Dog": "Do not expect the loyal Dog to howl at the moon out of blind devotion for an Ox mate. They have conflicting objectives. The Dog’s mission—advocating for the homeless in Alaska—is bound to take precedence. And the Ox? It will be championing a major corporation and earning fifty percent of the profits. These two are so divergent in their philosophies that minor disputes create deep rifts in their living room carpet. Despite a gentle, loving nature, a youthful Dog, blessed with clarity, understands that this is a fiercely competitive world, yet believes only in justice and equality. The Dog wants no part of the Ox’s arrogant dominance and responds solely to the call of the afflicted. The Ox believes that charity begins at home and will implore the Dog to disregard the world’s problems. Both are fervent moralizers, but they do not see eye to eye: the Dog argues about starving children in India, attempting to persuade the Ox to contribute to the noble cause; the Ox fights for justice at home, complaining that the money used to establish a shelter for the homeless last month was actually intended to pay for the children’s private school. Sexual intimacy between them can be enjoyable! This is the only area where an Ox's command to 'roll over' holds sway. The Dog is amused by and admires the Ox’s relentlessness and brutally frank style in bed. This is merely an acceptable marriage. No sexual fireworks or undying passion will keep these two very different people together.",
    "Pig": "Indeed, these two get along famously. The good-natured Pig is so adaptable that the Ox will eventually believe it truly is in charge. Let’s imagine that atop a beautiful hill in the mountains of some exquisite location, the Ox and the Pig own a home. This home is so meticulously cared for that it gleams. The Pig enjoys cooking and does not mind tidying up after dinner. Before bedtime, the careful Ox turns off all the lights and puts out the garbage and the cat. Then this affectionate pair settles into bed. It is ideal; they are well-matched. Early in the morning, they awaken to the sound of birds, which sets a harmonious tone for the day. Of course, the birds are fed daily by the disciplined Ox, who keeps this household running on a very strict schedule. But it is the Pig who purchases the birdseed. Pigs love animals, adore country life, and are lavishly generous. Sexual intimacy between these two country folk is lusty and fulfilling. The Ox is a bit conventional and unrefined at first, but the Pig’s rich sensuality soon takes over, and they enjoy creating a beautiful, leisurely lifetime of love.",
    },
    futures: {
        "2025": { "year": "Snake", "element": "Yin Wood", "prediction": "You and the Snake get along like fraternal twins. You do not resemble each other at all, yet you are inseparable companions. Snakes consistently possess an attractive quality and are not afraid of assuming power. The Snake's style never interferes with yours. You proceed steadily, while Snakes move subtly. However, you are both rather deliberate and profound thinkers. Hence, your wavelengths align, and you truly appreciate each other. You each enjoy a quiet, yet steadfast presence. You will be granted all manner of successes this year. Accolades, awards, and honors will come your way because the Snake admires you Ox individuals, and the feeling is mutual. Consume more fiber, take vitamins, and learn to accept the benefits of alternative medicine. If you have children or have the opportunity to borrow or care for some, you will find that you enjoy their company most in this Snake year. You (deliberate Ox that you are) may even find you can have fun at the theme park. An Ox on a roller coaster is not a common sight, but in a Snake year, such a sight is entirely plausible." },
        "2026": { "year": "Horse", "element": "Yang Fire", "prediction": "Due to the general atmosphere of diligent labor that characterizes all Horse years, this year will be fortunate for Oxen. It is no secret: you Oxen love to work and work hard. You possess an exceptional capacity for exertion—both physical and mental. Work energizes you. Why? Because you live for results and are not particularly concerned with how you achieve those results—even if you have to struggle uphill with a thousand-pound boulder on your weary shoulders—reaching the destination is always worth the effort. So when Horse years arrive, you are favored, applauded, and praised for your unparalleled work ethic. When the Japanese enslaved Koreans in a darker period of their history, it was commonly said: 'We worked them like Horses and Oxen.' No one works harder than you two. So in this Horse year, you may be working extremely hard, but the results will be precisely what you sought because the Horse's influence protects and preserves the Ox. It may not prove to be the most joyful year of your life... but then, when you have rich and tangible rewards from your work, who needs fun?" },
        "2027": { "year": "Goat", "element": "Yin Fire", "prediction": "Goats will irritate you. There is friction between you and the Goat because the Goat places more emphasis on the lighter side of life, desires to depend on a stronger being or institution, and is frequently not a self-starter. Goats may be geniuses, but they do not possess the kind of assertive presence and persistent spirit that you have. Goats often work in bursts—three or four sleepless nights at the computer followed by a week's rest is perfectly acceptable to them. Their perception of time is different. You, being determined, pre-programmed, and steady at the helm, cannot tolerate this erratic rhythm and alteration of schedules. You desire more stability in your daily life. So, in this Goat year, I suggest you retreat to the countryside. Purchase that château in the south of France, observe your grapes grow, harvest them, and transform them into wine; but do not attempt to compete for awards or honors. Avoid all contests. Enjoy your romantic life now. It can be a top priority because, in this frivolous Goat year, you will not need to spend all your time working. When you are not busy making love, why not plan your next business triumph? Next year, your Monkey friend will arrive. Monkeys allow Oxen to get away with a great deal." },
        "2028": { "year": "Monkey", "element": "Yang Earth", "prediction": "This year promises abundant activity and an acceleration of pace for you Oxen. I understand you do not enjoy rushing and dislike being told to move faster. But... Monkeys have no time to waste standing around impatiently while you Oxen contemplate and labor through mountains of what Monkeys consider useless details, paperwork, and administrative nonsense. Monkeys identify a problem, address its core, solve it, and move on to the next. So, you will have to abandon your spreadsheets, discard your precious bureaucracy, and learn to quicken your pace. And (because you are determined to advance no matter what) you will indeed accelerate. This hectic rhythm, however, may take a toll on your health. During this Monkey year, be sure to undergo regular checkups and tests for all potential ailments that can affect Oxen (especially digestion-related illnesses). The bottom line? You will thrive in a Monkey year because the Monkey is more astute than all of us and recognizes when it has found a sensible, reliable ally. That, my dear Ox friend, is you. This year will be fruitful, and you will not face sabotage or be denied much of anything. You will, however, need to pick up those heavy feet of yours and get moving." },
        "2029": { "year": "Rooster", "element": "Yin Earth", "prediction": "Rooster years are consistently beneficial for hardworking individuals, and you Oxen are no exception. However, as the recent Monkey year truly exhausted you and diminished your capacity for tolerating another's pace, you will tend to be reluctant to cooperate this year. Joint projects, group efforts, associations, and partnerships will suffer because you desire a year off from being an ally and companion to someone who is constantly frenetic. You simply wish to be your own person again and move at your own pleasant (slow) pace. For this year, then, I suggest you proceed independently. Continue working at whatever you enjoy and are confident will bring you success. But do not sign any contracts that oblige you to participate in meetings or agree to unpalatable clauses. You are simply not in the right frame of mind for joint ventures. Your romantic life suffered somewhat from the general turmoil of last year. Take some time to express affection and tenderness with your sweetheart or spouse this year. The Rooster enjoys your company and does not truly mind if you sneak away for a few romantic weekends. You always give your all when you return—and you are usually in a much better frame of mind as well. This sign is not called Rooster for nothing. Roosters appreciate the necessity of passion in the lives of their subjects. After all, isn't sexual prowess what Roosters are so famous for?" },
        "2030": { "year": "Dog", "element": "Yang Metal", "prediction": "The Dog poses no threat to you Oxen. A Dog can bark, growl, and snarl at a steadfast Ox for as long and as loudly as it wishes, and you will simply stand there, silent and Ox-like, waiting for its tantrum to subside. However, wisdom dictates that in Dog years, the Ox should remain out of the public eye. Why? Because the criticisms and outcries against injustice and demands for fair play in government, for which the Dog is so renowned, do not appeal to you. And if you were to join in, you might draw unwanted attention. You are not the type to carry a placard in the street or shout slogans in front of government buildings to achieve your goals. You are a slow-burning individual who waits, observes, and acts only when certain of a positive outcome. You might be clumsy, but you are not foolish enough to be upfront about how you would change things. You would rather die than spend a night in jail for participating in a riot over healthcare. Instead, you slowly push that rock up the hill, marking all paths with your name, and then you overthrow the entire government by swiftly rolling that massive boulder from the mountaintop onto the offenders' heads. That is what I mean by maintaining a low profile." },
        "2031": { "year": "Pig", "element": "Yin Metal", "prediction": "Oxen typically thrive during the early part of Pig Years. This year will be no exception. You will undoubtedly find both adventure and abundant enjoyment in the initial months. However, around June, just before summer begins, you will need to monitor your budget more closely than you have been. Quite suddenly, it will seem as though your bank account has developed a leak. Do verify all banking and investment statements, as computers tend to make more errors in Pig years. Being overly generous to those they love, Oxen also frequently fall victim to oversight or miscalculation. The Pig and the Ox are generally complicit in their pursuit of affluence for its own sake. You are equally skilled at accumulating not only money but also precious possessions—art and antiques, or vintage cars and outrageously expensive wines and caviar. So, in a luxury-loving Pig year, you will be tempted to purchase major artworks or cases of rare Bordeaux or Champagne. This may be one clue as to why that bank account is losing funds. Another possibility is the presence of a loved one who is draining you of resources he or she has not earned. Consult with your accountant more frequently, count those pennies, and remain vigilant for deception originating from those closest to you." },
        "2032": { "year": "Rat", "element": "Yang Water", "prediction": "Rats do not often trouble Oxen. The Rat's hyperactive temperament and the Ox's deliberate pace do not align. Yet, the Rat deeply admires your strength. So, in a Rat year, you Oxen will not be bothered or hindered in your progress. Rats simply do not interfere with Oxen. They respect your tenacity and endurance, and they appreciate the security you provide. All this year, you will be able to work at your own relaxed, steady rhythm, and you can anticipate achieving excellent results. You will earn more money and be offered a promotion to a more influential position. However, I advise you to decline the promotion. A more prestigious position will only add to your workload. It will also require more responsibility and a greater degree of public interaction, which might be detrimental to your well-being. A quiet, diligent, solitary life is what the Ox requires and desires. Public life, with all its fanfare and ceremony, would only make you irritable. Why not just enjoy the peace and quiet of your own home, with all its order and tranquility, and simply take the additional salary that comes with the job offer? The company will be just as pleased, and your liver will thank you for it." },
        "2033": { "year": "Ox", "element": "Yin Water", "prediction": "I must caution you against attempting to earn a significant amount of money or securing the prestigious job you desire in an Ox year. Why? It is not merely because the Ox does not wish for your success, but also because your rapid, opportunistic methods exasperate the Ox. As a long-term planner, the Ox becomes disoriented simply observing your quick acceleration and swift movements. Ox individuals possess great talent for leadership; they often become autocratic figures. However, they are not particularly quick on their feet, and they are even slower in their intellectual processing. Their minds operate in an unhurried fashion. Do they linger and adopt a leisurely approach to managing their year or their domain? Absolutely not. But they persevere steadily, and you act impulsively. Therefore, in an Ox year, it is advisable to preemptively temper your intensity so as not to appear threatening or to bewilder the deliberate, task-oriented Ox. You will not need to humble yourself to advance. However, you will need to agree with those in positions of authority. Since you detest being anyone's subordinate, you may experience digestive issues, migraines, and other stress-related ailments as a consequence. Maintain the well-being of your romantic life by making a special effort to perform loving acts of kindness and deference towards your beloved or spouse (or both) in this rather challenging, unaccommodating Ox year. You need all the approval and affection you can gather from those who cherish and admire your spirited demeanor." },
        "2034": { "year": "Tiger", "element": "Yang Wood", "prediction": "This year is your year. You are in charge. You must, therefore, be vigilant and ensure your subjects do not overthrow you. Do you recall that last year, you were able to spend your time peacefully managing your projects and were not subject to any sudden changes or unexpected events? Well, this year promises to be quite the opposite. The Tiger is an extremely volatile individual who enjoys a thrill a minute. You can handle the chaos, but you will not appreciate having to frequently revise your meticulously planned timetables. Tigers thrive on constant change, and you... well, you do not. I would like to be able to advise you to travel and avoid this hectic atmosphere. Unfortunately, the Tiger and the Ox are traditionally at odds. So, you must remain on guard. If you are not present and vigilant, your enemies will seize the opportunity to usurp your authority. Do not take risks. Do not change jobs or move to a new house. Do not buy a new car. Do not have a baby. Do not invest your money. The only advice I can offer you is: stay where you are, and do not make any significant moves." },
        "2035": { "year": "Rabbit", "element": "Yin Wood", "prediction": "You can anticipate significant success in the Cat/Rabbit year. In these years, individuals of your temperament are favored by the heavens. You may have experienced some challenging times in the past couple of years, but this year will bring you great joy and a multitude of rewarding experiences. You are a cautious individual who is not prone to making foolish mistakes in your work life or in your romantic entanglements. However, you tend to be overly strict in your judgments and do not easily accept the shortcomings of others. This year, if you can learn to be more tolerant and flexible, you will see a notable improvement in your interactions with others. Family members will show their gratitude with gifts and praise. It is likely that you will be offered a prestigious job that you have desired for a long time. Accept it! Your home life this year will be serene and peaceful. Any ongoing issues will dissipate by themselves. Even your physical health will be excellent. There is no need for you to undergo any plastic surgery or cosmetic procedures. The Cat/Rabbit is not concerned with appearance. Your natural dignity will suffice. So, you can relax. Everything is secure, your future is bright, and no one is attempting to undermine your authority. Enjoy it while you can. Next year promises to be a bit more challenging." },
        "2036": { "year": "Dragon", "element": "Yang Fire", "prediction": "You will be highly irritated by the atmosphere of the Dragon year. You enjoy tranquility and do not like to feel that you are being observed or judged. Dragons, on the other hand, are the exact opposite; they require an audience and thrive on being the center of attention. They will never comprehend why a gifted individual such as yourself prefers to work quietly in the background without fanfare or applause. Consequently, there will be friction between you and those in power this year. Since you cannot avoid them, you will have to find a way to navigate their flamboyant events and celebrations without appearing to be the wet blanket that you undoubtedly are. You might consider purchasing an expensive new car or a significant work of art to boost your confidence and allow you to attend those dreaded dinner parties in style. Or you could marry a beautiful, intelligent person to enhance your public image. In short, this year you need to devise strategies to make yourself more socially acceptable and to tolerate the extravagance that you despise. Alternatively, you could adopt some eccentric behavior yourself. Take up tap dancing, try skydiving, or join a rock-and-roll band. Doing so will ensure you are no longer the one judging others for their eccentricities, but the one being judged." }
    }
};

    